{{France-noble-stub}}

{{Distinguish|Agonal respiration}}
In medicine, an '''agonal heart rhythm''' is a variant of [[asystole]]. Agonal heart rhythm is usually ventricular in origin. Occasional [[P wave (electrocardiography)|P waves]] and [[QRS complexes]] can be seen on the [[electrocardiogram]]. The complexes tend to be wide and bizarre in morphological appearance.<ref> Garcia T, Miller B. Arrhythmia Recognition: The Art of Interpretation. Jones and Bartlett, Sudbury MA: 2004.</ref> Clinically, an agonal rhythm is regarded as asystole and should be treated equivalently, with [[cardiopulmonary resuscitation]] and administration of [[intravenous]] [[adrenaline]].<ref name=resus>[https://www.resus.org.uk/pages/alsalgo.pdf UK Resuscitation Council. Adult advanced life support algorithm. 2010.]</ref> As in asystole, the prognosis for a patient presenting with this rhythm is very poor. Sometimes this appears after asystole or after a failed resurrection attempt.
==See also== * [[Asystole]] * [[Cardiac arrest]] * [[Myocardial infarction]] * [[Ventricular fibrillation]]
