{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Chorea gravidarum | image = | caption = | | pronounce = | field = | synonyms = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Chorea gravidarum''' is a rare<ref name="pmid5742087">{{cite journal |pmid=5742087 |year=1968 |author1=Zegart |first1=K. N. |title=Chorea gravidarum |journal=Obstetrics and gynecology |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=24–7 |last2=Schwarz |first2=R. H. }}</ref> type of [[chorea (disease)|chorea]] which presents with involuntary abnormal movement, characterized by abrupt, brief, nonrhythmic, nonrepetitive movement of any limb, often associated with nonpatterned facial grimaces. It is a complication of [[pregnancy]] which can be associated with [[eclampsia]] and its effects upon the [[basal ganglia]]. It is not an causal or pathologically distinct entity but a generic term for chorea of any cause starting during pregnancy. It is associated with history of [[Sydenham's chorea]]. It mostly occurs in young patients; the average age is 22 years.<ref name="Willson Preece 471">{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archinte.1932.00150100128011 |title=Chorea Gravidarum |journal=Archives of Internal Medicine |volume=49 |issue=3 |pages=471–533 |year=1932 |last1=Willson |first1=Prentiss }}</ref><ref name="Willson Preece 671">{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archinte.1932.00150110134008 |title=Chorea Gravidarum |journal=Archives of Internal Medicine |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=671–97 |year=1932 |last1=Willson |first1=Prentiss }}</ref>
Recently there has been a decline in incidence which is probably the result of a decline in [[rheumatic fever]] ([[rheumatic fever|RF]]), which was a major cause of chorea gravidarum before the use of [[antibiotics]] for [[streptococcal pharyngitis]].
==Pathophysiology== Several pathogenetic mechanisms for chorea gravidarum have been offered, but none have been proven. History of either [[rheumatic fever]] or chorea is suspected:<ref name="Willson Preece 471"/><ref name="Willson Preece 671"/> the suggestion is that [[estrogens]] and [[progesterone]] may sensitize [[dopamine]] receptors (presumably at a [[Striatum|striatal level]]) and induce chorea in individuals who are vulnerable to this complication by virtue of preexisting [[pathology]] in the [[basal ganglia]]. The relation to rheumatic fever was strengthened by many studies that showed that women with normal pregnancies before rheumatic fever developed chorea in subsequent pregnancies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Black |first1=M |title=Two cases of chorea in pregnancy |journal=Glasgow Medical Journal |year=1900 |pages=441–4 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Matthews |first1=AA |title=Chorea complicating pregnancy |journal=Northwest Med |year=1911 |volume=15 |pages=372 }}</ref> At least 35% of patients have a definite history of acute rheumatic fever and [[Sydenham chorea]]; 4% of those with chorea gravidarum had [[acute rheumatic fever]].<ref name="Willson Preece 471"/><ref name="Willson Preece 671"/>
It has been suggested that use of oral contraceptives is an infrequent cause of chorea. A patient developed this chorea with no definite evidence of previous Sydenham's chorea or recent streptoccocal infections, but had anti-basal ganglia [[antibodies]], suggesting [[Autoimmune disease|immunological]] basis for the pathophysiology of this chorea.<ref name="pmid14742621">{{cite journal |pmid=14742621 |pmc=1738905 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.2003.019851 |url=http://jnnp.bmj.com/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=14742621 |year=2004 |author1=Miranda |first1=M |title=Oral contraceptive induced chorea: Another condition associated with anti-basal ganglia antibodies |journal=Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry |volume=75 |issue=2 |pages=327–8 |last2=Cardoso |first2=F |last3=Giovannoni |first3=G |last4=Church |first4=A }}</ref><ref name="pmid10856942">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0166-2236(00)01575-7 |pmid=10856942 |title=Pathogenetic role of autoantibodies in neurological diseases |journal=Trends in Neurosciences |volume=23 |issue=7 |pages=317–27 |year=2000 |last1=Archelos |first1=Juan J. |last2=Hartung |first2=Hans-Peter }}</ref>
==Diagnosis== ===Differential diagnoses=== {{div col|colwidth=22em}} *[[Pelizaeus–Merzbacher disease]] *[[Pantothenate kinase-associated neurodegeneration]] *[[Ramsay Hunt syndrome]] *[[Huntington's disease]] *[[Multiple system atrophy|Striatonigral degeneration]] *[[Lesch–Nyhan syndrome]] *[[Systemic lupus erythematosus]] *[[Lyme disease]] *[[Torticollis]] *[[Multiple system atrophy]] *[[Tourette syndrome]] and other tic disorders *[[Neuroacanthocytosis]] *[[Viral encephalitis]] *[[Neuronal ceroid lipofuscinosis]] *[[Wilson's disease]] *[[Olivopontocerebellar atrophy]] *[[Familial paroxysmal choreoathetosis]] *[[Benign hereditary chorea]]<ref>{{EMedicine|article|1149725|Chorea Gravidarum}}</ref> {{div col end}} Chorea can also be a manifestation of drug toxicity (for example, [[anticonvulsants]], [[antiparkinson drug|antiparkinson agents]], [[neuroleptics]], [[steroids]], and [[estrogen]]), or a result of an infectious disease such as [[meningovascular syphilis]], [[Lyme disease]], [[viral encephalitis]], and many others.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}
==Treatment== Drug treatment is indicated for patients with severe disabling chorea. It is treated with [[haloperidol]],<ref name="pmid4643046">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0022-3476(72)80272-5 |pmid=4643046 |title=Rheumatic chorea controlled with haloperidol |journal=The Journal of Pediatrics |volume=81 |issue=6 |pages=1216–7 |year=1972 |last1=Axley |first1=John }}</ref><ref name="pmid472859">{{cite journal |doi=10.1097/00007611-197909000-00044 |pmid=472859 |title=Treatment of Chorea Gravidarum with Haloperidol |journal=Southern Medical Journal |volume=72 |issue=9 |pages=1220–1 |year=1979 |last1=Patterson |first1=John F. }}</ref><ref name="pmid7078886">{{cite journal |pmid=7078886 |url=http://journals.lww.com/greenjournal/abstract/1982/03000/control_of_chorea_gravidarum_with_haloperidol.23.aspx |year=1982 |author1=Donaldson |first1=J. O. |title=Control of chorea gravidarum with haloperidol |journal=Obstetrics and gynecology |volume=59 |issue=3 |pages=381–2 }}</ref> [[chlorpromazine]] alone or in combination with [[diazepam]], and also [[pimozide]], which is another neuroleptic drug which may have fewer adverse effects than haloperidol.<ref name="pmid2296371">{{cite journal |doi=10.1212/wnl.40.1.186 |pmid=2296371 |title=Pimozide treatment of Sydenham's chorea |journal=Neurology |volume=40 |issue=1 |pages=186 |year=1990 |last1=Shannon |first1=K. M. |last2=Fenichel |first2=G. M. }}</ref> [[Valproic acid]], [[chloral hydrate]], [[risperidone]], or [[phenobarbital]] can also be used.<ref>{{EMedicine|article|1149725|Chorea Gravidarum|treatment}}</ref>
