'''Pongsaklek Wonjongkam''' ({{lang-th|พงษ์ศักดิ์เล็ก วันจงคำ}}; born: August 11, 1977) is a Thai former [[professional boxer]] and current boxing trainer. He is a two-time former [[Lineal championship|lineal flyweight]] champion.

== Professional career ==
Wonjongkam had a record of 9-2 early in his career. Both losses were to [[Filipino people|Filipino]] journeyman Jerry Pahayahay, whom Wonjongkam would defeat by 10-round decision in February, 1998.<ref name="boxrec">BoxRec.com editors. [http://www.boxrec.com/boxer_display.php?boxer_id=034051 "Pongsaklek Wonjongkam."] [[Boxrec.com|BoxRec.com]]. [[Uniform Resource Locator|URL]] accessed 5 July 2006.</ref> Since his second loss on July 11, 1996 to July 18, 2007, Wonjongkam won 55 consecutive bouts, the longest continuous win streak in boxing at the time.

On March 28, 1997 Wonjongkam knocked out [[Mzukisi Sikali]] of [[South Africa]] in 48 seconds to win the [[World Boxing Union|WBU]] [[Light Flyweight]] Championship. Sikali would go on to hold both the [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] [[List of IBO world champions#Flyweight|Flyweight]] and [[World Boxing Union|WBU]] [[Super Flyweight]] titles.

=== WBC Flyweight Champion ===
On March 2, 2001, Wonjongkam fought [[Malcolm Tuñacao]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] and [[List of lineal boxing world champions#Flyweight|Lineal Flyweight]] Championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/fly.htm|title=Pongsaklek Wonjongkam - Lineal Flyweight Champion|publisher=The Cyber Boxing Zone Encyclopedia}}</ref> Tuñacao won the Flyweight Lineage Championship from [[Medgoen Singsurat]], who won the title by knocking out [[Manny Pacquiao]]. Pacquiao would later become the number one [[pound for pound]] fighter in the world. Wonjongkam won by first-round TKO after knocking Tuñacao down three times.<ref name="boxrec"/>

In his fourth Lineal and WBC Flyweight title defense, on April 19, 2002, Wonjongkam knocked out [[Japanese people|Japanese]] flyweight titleholder [[Daisuke Naito]] in 34 seconds.<ref name="boxrec"/> This knockout set the record for fastest knockout in division history.<ref name="sweetscience">Mallon, Scott. [http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2546/boxing-asia/ "Boxing in Asia."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060908232224/http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2546/boxing-asia/ |date=2006-09-08 }} 24 August 2005. ''The Sweet Science.'' URL accessed 7 July 2006.</ref>

On November 17, 2006, Wonjongkam defeated [[South African people|South African]] boxer Monelisi Mhikiza Myekeni by unanimous decision.<ref name="boxrec"/> Wonjongkam set the flyweight division record for consecutive title defenses, 16, with this victory.<ref name="record">Jackson, Ron. [http://www.superboxing.co.za/default.asp?id=183774&des=article&scat=superboxing/international "Flyweight champ wins 15th defence."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060930172733/http://www.superboxing.co.za/default.asp?id=183774&des=article&scat=superboxing%2Finternational |date=2006-09-30 }} ''SuperBoxing''. URL accessed 5 July 2006.</ref>

Wonjongkam was ranked number ten in [[Ring Magazine pound for pound|''Ring'' magazine's pound-for-pound rankings]], but [[Jermain Taylor]] bumped him off the list on June 18, 2006. Wonjongkam was ranked as ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'''s number one flyweight<ref name="thering">''The Ring'' editors. [http://www.thering-online.com/ringpages/ratings2.html ''The Ring'' Ratings.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051224024727/http://www.thering-online.com/ringpages/ratings2.html |date=2005-12-24 }} 3 July 2006. ''The Ring''. URL accessed 7 July 2006</ref> until his loss to Daisuke Naito in 2007.

=== Losing the Title ===
Wonjongkam suffered a shocking upset decision loss to [[Daisuke Naito]] in July, 2007, ending his long run as champion. Wonjongkam had defeated Naito twice in previous titles defenses. On March 8, 2008, Wonjongkam faced Naito in a rematch which ended in a draw.

=== Wonjongkam vs. Miranda ===
Wonjongkam won the vacant [[Interim championship|Interim]] WBC Flyweight Championship in a bout against Mexican [[Julio César Miranda]] on April 24, 2009. The 12 round bout ended by a unanimous decision. Wonjongkam defended his interim title against Takahisa Masuda by knockout, setting the stage for a bout against Lineal WBC Flyweight Champion [[Koki Kameda]], who had recently defeated Naito to win the title.

=== Recapturing the WBC Flyweight Championship ===
On March 27, 2010, Wonjongkam fought Lineal Champion, [[Koki Kameda]], to unify the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Flyweight Championship and Interim [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Flyweight Championship. The winner would also claim the vacant [[The Ring (magazine)|''The Ring'']] Flyweight Championship.<ref>http://www.ringtv.com/blog/1757/weekend_peview_huge_weekend/</ref> Wonjongkam defeated Kameda by a 12-round majority decision to become the WBC and Ring Flyweight Champion.

=== Losing the WBC Flyweight Championship ===
On March 2, 2012, Wonjongkam lost his Lineal, ''The Ring'' and WBC Flyweight Titles in an upset technical knockout stoppage to [[Sonny Boy Jaro]] of Philippines. He was knocked down five times before the fight was stopped in the sixth round.

=== Later career ===
Wonjongkam won the vacant [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] International flyweight title against Hyobu Nakagama on August 31, 2012. However, he lost the title to Rey Migreno on November 1, 2012, by a third-round TKO, marking Wonjongkam's fifth defeat. Even more disappointingly for Wonjongkam, Migreno had a losing record of 17-20-3 going into this fight, and had been beaten twice before by Wonjongkam, first by ten-round UD in October 2007, and a first round stoppage in July 2010.

